Example: Table Inheritance (PostgreSQL only)
PostgreSQL supports table inheritance

MySQL does NOT.

PostgreSQL example
CREATE TABLE users (
  id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
  name TEXT
);

CREATE TABLE admins (
  role TEXT
) INHERITS (users);


Now:

INSERT INTO admins (name, role)
VALUES ('Shubham', 'super_admin');


And this works ğŸ‘‡

SELECT * FROM users;


â¡ï¸ It returns both users AND admins

Why this proves Object-Relational behavior

admins inherits columns from users

Acts like class inheritance

Parent table can query child records

This is not possible in MySQL

ğŸ“Œ MySQL has no table inheritance at all â€” you must use joins or STI-like patterns.

Interview one-liner ğŸ¯

PostgreSQL supports table inheritance, where one table can inherit another like classes, which is a core object-relational feature not available in MySQL.




###### example

n PostgreSQL, string is not a valid data type. You need to use VARCHAR, TEXT, etc.

âŒ Whatâ€™s wrong
name string,
email string


Postgres doesnâ€™t have a string type (thatâ€™s more of a Rails / ORM concept).

âœ… Correct PostgreSQL syntax (using inheritance)
CREATE TABLE users (
  name  TEXT,
  email TEXT
);

CREATE TABLE admins (
  role TEXT
) INHERITS (users);


This is valid Postgres syntax, and admins will inherit:

name

email

from the users table.

âš ï¸ Important Postgres inheritance gotchas (interview gold)

Postgres table inheritance is rarely used in real apps. A few key things to know:

1ï¸âƒ£ Queries on parent donâ€™t include children by default (unless you want them to)
SELECT * FROM users;


â¬†ï¸ This will include admins rows by default.

To get only users (excluding admins):

SELECT * FROM ONLY users;

2ï¸âƒ£ Constraints are NOT fully inherited

PRIMARY KEY

UNIQUE

FOREIGN KEY

ğŸ‘‰ These do NOT automatically apply to child tables.

Example:

ALTER TABLE users ADD CONSTRAINT users_email_unique UNIQUE (email);


â¬†ï¸ This does NOT enforce uniqueness across admins.

This is one big reason people avoid inheritance.

3ï¸âƒ£ Rails does NOT support Postgres inheritance

ActiveRecord:

doesnâ€™t understand inherited tables

wonâ€™t auto-load columns correctly

causes pain with validations & associations

ğŸ‘‰ Rails prefers:

Single Table Inheritance (STI), or

Separate tables with foreign keys

âœ… Rails-friendly alternative (recommended)

If this is for a Rails system:

Option 1: STI (most common)
# users table
type:string
name:string
email:string
role:string

class User < ApplicationRecord; end
class Admin < User; end

Option 2: Separate tables (clean + explicit)
users(id, name, email)
admins(id, user_id, role)

